AGI - New Caledonia> is iron and fire for the rebellion of the Independents against an electoral reform voted by the French Parliament, which led President Emmanuel Macron> to decree the state of emergency. After two nights of unrest, shooting with large arms, the budget is four dead, including a young agent. The epicenter of the revolt is Nouméa, the capital, where the airport was closed until new order. At the end of a meeting of the National Defence and Security Council, convened urgently in Paris, decombusting the government agenda, the president denounced "the intolerable violence that will be faced with an implacable response to ensure the return of the Republican order", recalling "the need to resume political dialogue". The Prime Minister, Gabriel Attal, said that he will propose a date for a meeting in Paris "in the coming hours" with the parties involved to "continue dialogue" and "build" a "global political solution". However, he emphasized the premier, at the moment "the priority is to restore order, calm and serenity".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"When a gendarme is attacked, it is the Republic to be targeted. The guilty will be found and will pay for this crime," said the minister for the regions of Oltremare, Marie Guévenoux, who expressed his "immense emotion" for the death of a 22-year-old gendarme in New Caledonia.&nbsp; The agent, who belonged to the squadron of Melun (Seine-et-Marne), was struck by a gunshot to the head, in the field of Plum, not far from Nouméa, in the south of the archipelago. The other victims, according to the High Commissioner of the Republic in New Caledonia, Louis Le Franc, were wounded by gunshots allegedly exploded by militiamen and armed people, in an attempt to defend themselves from the police or gendarmerie, deploring an "insurrectional" situation.
&nbsp;
In New Caledonia "it goes straight towards civil war," the French High Commissioner warned. Yesterday evening, the National Assembly adopted the contested draft constitutional reform extending the electorate in New Caledonia. The loyalists call for the adoption of the text, while the Kanak independentists call for the withdrawal. President Macron announced that he would convene the Congress "before the end of June" to ratify this reform, unless pro-independence and loyalist parties were able to reach an agreement on a more complete text by that date.&nbsp; At the moment five local political groups - the Union cale'donienne-Front de libe'ration nationale kanak et socialiste (UC-FLNKS) and nationalists, the Union nationale pour l'inde'pendance (UNI), Les Loyalistes, Rassemblement and Eveil oce'anien (EO) - issued a joint press release "
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
For the daily Le Monde, the chaos in which New Caledonia is now the result of the "dramatic failure of a method>". In fact, the reform of the electoral body of the archipelago is the 'goccia' that has made the vase overflow. "What could seem a slow process towards democracy is vented into a virtual climate of civil war, because there are still strong inequalities in the kanak people. The economic context, marked by the crisis of nickel, is not good, the young people dispose of finding a future and the government, instead of doing everything possible to favor an agreement between the parties, has given the impression of prolonging for one of the two parts", analyzed the French daily. The decision of President Macron to entrust the management of the dossier to the Interior Minister, Ge'rald Darmanin, when Matignon - the Premier's office - had always conducted the negotiations after Michel Rocard, was badly received.
&nbsp;
The appointment as Secretary of State in 2022 of the non-independent president of the South Province, Sonia Backe's, increased the suspicions, as well as the appointment as rapporteur of the draft constitutional law of another loyalist elected by the Rocca, Nicolas Metzdorf, at a time when the challenge is to succeed in defining the future links of New Caledonia with France, in a framework of decolonization. In recent months three former prime ministers, Jean-Marc Ayrault, Manuel Valls and Edouard Philippe, > had launched the alarm, in vain. It is actually the story that is repeated, dramatically and ineluctably. Today's uprising, led by young people turned out from the control of the pro-independence leaders who had called to mobilize against the text, reaches 40 years from the beginning of the quasi-civil war that led to the death of 19 kanak and two soldiers during the assault on the Ouvéa cave, on May 5, 1988. At the time, it was the definition of the electorate to create an undeniable gap between loyalists and independentists. Since then, three referendums have confirmed the will of the inhabitants of New Caledonia to remain French, without being able to overcome the distrust among communities.
&nbsp;
During this long process, only those who were registered in the electoral lists before the agreement were allowed to vote. As a result, almost one out of five voters are currently excluded from ballots. The text voted by Parliament partially corrects this inequality by opening the electorate to all natives and people living in New Caledonia for at least 10 years. Despite everything, maintaining the bill before the National Assembly yesterday and putting it to the votes, the executive of Attal, supported by the majority, the right and the extreme right, wanted to give a lesson of firmness to the riots: it does not yield to violence. In addition, he tried to quickly secure a legal basis in view of the forthcoming provincial elections, which will have to be kept to the maximum by 2025, since the text has already been approved by the Senate. "But it is a victory of Pirro, because nothing will be possible without a broad agreement that includes economic, social and institutional issues," he concluded "Le Monde".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

