AGI - &nbsp;The Prime Minister of Slovakia, Robert Fico, is in serious condition at the hospital of the town of Banska' Bystrica, in the center of the country and 200 kilometers from the capital Bratislava, after being wounded with 5 gunshots fired at the end of a government meeting in Gandlova and having suffered a long surgery at the end of which he was placed in a pharmacological coma. Less than a month from the European elections, Slovakia is very divided and the political debate very fierce among the supporters of the 50-year-old prime minister, who has Eurosceptic and anti-Nato positions as well as anti-Ukraine, and its pro-European and Atlantean opponents. Representatives of the government spoke of the "most sad moment in the history of the country", born on January 1, 1993 from the division of Czechoslovakia in two different countries, the Czech Republic with capital Prague and 10,5 million inhabitants and Slovakia populated by 5.5 million people.<br> &nbsp;
<div </div
<br Defense Minister Robert Kaliniak spoke of "a political attack" to which "react accordingly". The police arrested the manager, a 71-year-old writer named Juraj Cintula, who said he acted because "not agree with the politics of this government." Back to power as prime minister last October (he was already head of the government of Bratislava from 2006 to 2010 and from 2012 to 2018), Fico has as first political action interrupted military support to Ukraine. Already a member of the Communist Party, he opposed EU sanctions against Russia. Last month his ally Peter Pellegrini won the presidential elections by defeating the European opponent. The most controversial decision was the adoption of a bill on radio and public television that according to opponents limits freedom of press.
<div </div
&nbsp;
The main party of opposition Slovakia progressively denied the hypothesis that the attacker is somehow linked to political formation and leader Michal Simeka warned "against the spread of false information about the author of the murder". The whole world condemned the attack on Fico: from Biden to Putin, from Macron to Von der Leyen, from Meloni to Scholz, from Stoltenberg to Guterres, from Zelensky to the nearby and allied Orban, everyone was shocked and defined the "unreachable" attack. &nbsp;
